  "prompt": "My mom makes me eat less than my BMR for weight loss. what should I do?",
  "response": "It\u2019s important to approach weight loss in a healthy and sustainable way. Eating less than your Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) can be harmful and counterproductive. Here\u2019s what you should consider doing:\n\n### 1. **Understand BMR and Caloric Needs**\n   - Your BMR is the number of calories your body needs to maintain basic functions (like breathing and circulation) at rest.\n   - Eating below your BMR for extended periods can lead to nutrient deficiencies, muscle loss, fatigue, and a slower metabolism.\n   - A safe and effective weight loss plan typically involves eating slightly below your **Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE)**, which includes your BMR plus calories burned through activity.\n\n### 2. **Communicate with Your Mom**\n   - Calmly explain that eating below your BMR can have negative effects on your health.\n   - Share that sustainable weight loss involves a balanced approach, including a moderate calorie deficit, proper nutrition, and regular physical activity.\n\n### 3. **Seek Professional Guidance**\n   - Consult a **registered dietitian or nutritionist** to create a personalized, healthy meal plan that supports weight loss without compromising your health.\n   - A doctor can also help ensure your weight loss goals are safe and appropriate for your age, body type, and overall health.\n\n### 4. **Focus on Nutrient-Dense Foods**\n   - Instead of drastically cutting calories, focus on eating nutrient-dense, whole foods (like vegetables, lean proteins, whole grains, and healthy fats) that keep you full and energized.\n   - Avoid empty calories from sugary or highly processed foods.\n\n### 5. **Incorporate Physical Activity**\n   - Combine a balanced diet with regular exercise to support weight loss and overall health.\n   - Strength training and cardio can help you maintain muscle mass and boost your metabolism.\n\n### 6. **Prioritize Mental Health**\n   - Weight loss should not come at the expense of your mental or emotional well-being.\n   - If you feel pressured or stressed about your eating habits, talk to someone you trust or consider seeking support from a counselor.\n\n### Key Takeaway\nEating below your BMR is not a healthy or sustainable way to lose weight. Focus on a balanced approach that includes a moderate calorie deficit, nutritious foods, and regular exercise. If your mom\u2019s approach is causing you stress or harm, seek help from a professional to guide you both toward a healthier plan.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
